"ideally i'd have something similar to `pytest` where we can just run a series of benchmarks under certaing conditions (e.g. tensor backend etc..) which produces a summary on the cmd line or as a txt file\r\n\r\nmaybe this is useful?\r\n\r\nhttp://pytest-benchmark.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html\n\n@lukasheinrich So, using [`pytest-benchmark`](http://pytest-benchmark.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html) it seems (to me so far at least) that we need to define a test function for every benchmark we want. I can check into this more (maybe ask the devs). So we can't just loop.\r\n\r\nIf we cant to use this (which I think we should) then to start off with some benchmarks on bins to expand upon the most important thing is just the number of bins, not necessarily the content (as long as it is somewhat reasonable), correct? Let me know if my question is confusing (it isn't phrased perhaps the best).\n\nActually I think that [this Issue](https://github.com/ionelmc/pytest-benchmark/issues/48) might help out. I'll follow up tonight.\n\n@matthewfeickert yeah, i think a simple test that just clones the same single bin N times should be sufficient to observe a 0th approximation of the scaling behaviour. later on we might fuzz this out and e.g. have randomized tests"